ROSCOE
TURNE
R
Establishing a new transcontinental record of thirteen hours
and thirty-five minutes in his flight from the east to the west
coast, Colonel Roscoe Turner cut two hours and seventeen
minutes from the previous mark. His Wasp Junior powered
Wedell-Williams Special averaged approximately two hundred
miles an hour for the two thousand five hundred miles separating
Los Angeles from New York.
Strong head winds on the
occasion of his flight retarded him tremendously.
Notwith-
standing this, however, his record stands as one of the most
outstanding of the year. Renowned as one of America's premier
speed pilots, Colonel Turner has flown more than a quarter
million miles behind Pratt and Whitney engines.
The implicit
confidence which he has placed in them has always been
justified. His records stand as evidence of their performance.
A ME
HAIZ LIP
By outmarking all entries in his speed dash from Los Angeles
to Cleveland Jimmie Haizlip won the Bendix Trophy for 1932.
Not satisfied with this achievement alone, he continued on to
New York, and by clipping fifty-seven minutes from the previous
record he established a new transcontinental west to east mark
of ten hours and nineteen minutes.
From coast to coast in
less than a half day and traveling at an average speed of two
hundred and forty-two miles an hour is the grueling test to
which his Wasp Junior was placed.
At altitudes ranging
from sea level to eighteen thousand feet and through a range of
corresponding temperatures every throb of its mechanical heart
was registered with unending precision.
Achievements of this
nature bespeak praise for pilot, plane and engine.
They are ef-
fected only through the perfection and coordination of all three.
